NFS Setup in TrueNAS
1. Create a Dataset
Go to Storage → Pools
Click ⋮ (3 dots) next to the pool → Add Dataset
Give a name → e.g., nfspool
Set:
Share Type: Generic
Case Sensitivity: Sensitive
Save
2. Set Permissions
Go to Storage → Datasets
Select nfs_share
Click Edit Permissions
Choose:
User: root
Group: wheel
Mode: Read/Write
Apply
3. Configure NFS Service
Go to Services
Enable NFS
Click the wrench icon:
Check Enable NFSv4
Number of servers: default
Bind IPs
Save and start the service
4. Create NFS Share
Go to Shares → Unix Shares (NFS)
Click Add
Set:
Path: /mnt/nfspool/nfs_share
Maproot User: root or nobody
Maproot Group: nogroup
Allowed networks or hosts: your client IPs
Save and enable
5. Mount NFS on Client (Linux)
sudo apt install nfs-common -y
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/nfs
sudo mount -t nfs -o nfsvers=4 192.168.101.130:/mnt/nfspool /mnt/nfs

WebDAV Setup in TrueNAS
1. Create Dataset
Storage → Add Dataset
Name it students
Save
2. Set Permissions
Select webdav
Edit Permissions
Select:
User: root
Group: wheel
Mode: Read / Write
Save
3. Create WebDAV Share
Shares → WebDAV → Add
Path: /mnt/webpool/webdav
Enable:
Read/Write
Authentication Required
Save
4. Enable WebDAV Service
Services → WebDAV
Enable Service
Configure:
Protocol: HTTP + HTTPS 
Listen IP: All
    Start the service

SMB (Windows File Sharing) Setup in TrueNAS
1. Create a Dataset
Storage → Pools
Add Dataset → name it smbpool
Set:
Share Type: 5MB
Save
2. Set Permissions
Storage → Datasets → Select smbpool
Edit Permissions
Choose a user/group:
User: root
Group: wheel
Save
3. Enable SMB Service
Services → SMB → Enable
Configure:
Workgroup: WORKGROUP
Enable SMB2/SMB3
Save & start
4. Create SMB Share
Shares → Windows Shares (SMB) → Add
Path: /mnt/smbpool
Name: smbshare
Enable:
Allow Guest Access (optional)
Browsable
Save
5. Access Share
Run in windows File Explorer
192.168.101.130\smbpool
